<p>The writers I know who are really good, are trying to be precise and effective rather than flowery or impressive.</p>

<p>This is true even for poets, especially for poets.</p>

<p>I studied poetry with a MacArthur Fellow (a genius award winner). He gave us this exercise to learn to write poetry (we literally did this in class).</p>

<p>We had 12 people in class seated around a conference table. He sent 4 people out of the room. He got a couple of people to help him place a block of lead the size of big lunch box on the table.Â </p>

<p>Then he turned to the 1st person at the table and said, â€œIâ€™m going to let one person into the room from the hall. And Iâ€™m going to ask that person to lift this block. You have two or three sentences to tell the person whatever you want so that he wonâ€™t be surprised by how heavy the block is.â€</p>

<p>We did that four times. Once for each person out in the hall.</p>

<p>Even though we were in poetry class, people start with the obvious. â€œItâ€™s heavy. Itâ€™s really heavy. Itâ€™s really, really heavy.â€</p>

<p>You find out very quickly that doesnâ€™t work. We also figured out very quickly that the challenge was to give the person in the hall the experience of lifting a block too heavy to lift, before they try to lift it.</p>

<p>So, you get into, â€œThis block is too heavy to lift.â€ But even that doesâ€™t work well because people think about heavy suitcases that you can drag around but canâ€™t lift.</p>

<p>So, you resort to hyperbole, â€œYou wonâ€™t believe how heavy this is. It will shock you how heavy this is.â€ That kind of works.</p>

<p>But then you go to metaphor, And you quickly get to some surprising and satisfying turns of phrases. â€œThis block is like a mountain in a lunch pail.â€ Not because youâ€™re trying to be witty, but because youâ€™re really trying to communicate how the block wonâ€™t even budge, wonâ€™t give a bit. And the metaphor seems to hold hope.Â </p>

<p>This became our goal in writing poetry. Imagine that youâ€™re talking to a reader. And the reader wonâ€™t ever be able to experience what you are experiencing. So, you want to describe it so precisely, that if he ever did experience it, he would not be surprised in the least.</p>

<p>And we found that when we set that as a goal, our writing got very creative and effective very quickly.</p>

