<p>Cousin Lenâ€™s Wonderful Adjective Cellar</p>

<p>COUSIN LEN FOUND HIS wonderful adjective cellar in a pawnshop. He haunts dusty Second Avenue pawnshops because theyâ€™re such a relief, he says, from Nature. Cousin Len doesnâ€™t like Nature very much. He spends most of his days outdoors gathering material for The Lure and Lore of the Woods, which he writes, and he would rather, he says, be a plumber. So he tours the pawnshops in his spare time, bringing home stereoscopic sets (Worldâ€™s Fair views, Chicago, 1893), watches that strike the hours, and china horses which hold toothpicks in their mouths. We admire these things very much, my wife and I. Weâ€™ve been living with Cousin Len since I got out of the Army, waiting to find a place of our own. So we admired the adjective cellar, too. It had the grace of line of a fire hydrant, but was slightly smaller and made of pewter. We thought it was a salt cellar, and so did Cousin Len. He discovered it was really an adjective cellar when he was working on his column one day after he bought it. â€œThe jewel-bedecked branches of the faery forest are funereally silent,â€ he had written. â€œThe icy, steel-like grip of winter has stilled their summâ€™ry, verdant murmur. And the silvâ€™ry, flutelike notes of its myriad, rainbow-dipped birds are gone.â€ At this point, naturally, he rested. And began to examine his salt cellar. He studied the bottom for the makerâ€™s mark, turning it in his hands, the cap an inch from his paper. And presently he saw that his manuscript had changed. â€œThe                         branches of the          forest are           silent,â€ he read. â€œThe                  grip of winter has stilled their                murmur. And the                  notes of its                            birds are gone.â€ Now, Cousin Len is no fool, and he knows an improvement when he sees it. He went back to work, writing as he always did, but he made his column twice as long. And then he applied the adjective cellar, moving it back and forth like a magnet, scan