<p>Mrs. Gorman passed under our window one day with Mrs. Miller, coming from the delicatessen. And a little flurry of adjectives and adverbs blew right into the middle of what she was saying. â€œPrices, these halcyon days,â€ she remarked, â€œare evanescent, transcendental, and simply terrible. Mark my maniacal words, things are going straight and pre-eminently to the coruscated, indomitable, allegorical dogs.â€ Mrs. Gorman was pretty surprised, of course, but she carried it off beautifully, smiling grandly and patronizingly at Mrs. Miller. She has always contended that her ancestors were kings; now she claims they were also poets. I suggested to Cousin Len, one time, that he save his adjectives, pack them into neatly labeled jars or cans, and sell them to the advertising agencies. Len pointed out, however, that we could never in a lifetime supply them in the quantities needed. We did, though, save up several shoe boxes full which we took along on a sight-seeing trip to Washington. And there, in the visitorsâ€™ gallery over the Senate, we cautiously emptied them into a huge electric fan which blew over the floor. They spread out in a great cloud and drifted down right through a tremendous debate. Something must have gone wrong this time, though, for things didnâ€™t sound one bit different. Weâ€™re still using the wonderful adjective cellar, and Cousin Lenâ€™s columns are getting better every day. A collection of them appeared in book form recently, which youâ€™ve probably read. And thereâ€™s talk of selling the movie rights. We also find Cousin Lenâ€™s adjective cellar helpful in composing telegrams, and I used it, mostly at the inch-and-a-half level, in writing this. Which is why itâ€™s so short, of course. â€“ Ladiesâ€™ Home Journal, April 1948</p>

