Application Essay Tips from Jack Finney</p>

<p>Iâ€™m staging an intervention. Cut back on the adjectives before they ruin you. If you remember just one of todayâ€™s application essay tips, remember that one. In a Ladies Home Journal article from 1948, science fiction writer Jack Finney mocks adjectives. Letâ€™s see what other application essay tips we can glean from his piece entitledCousin Lenâ€™s Wonderful Adjective Cellar.
6 Application Essay Tips from an â€œAdjective Cellarâ€ (whatever that is)</p>

<p>According to Wikipedia, before we had salt shakers, we had salt cellars: glass or silver vessels for holding salt. An adjective cellar is, wellâ€¦Iâ€™ll let Mr. Finney explain. What application essay tips can we learn from Finneyâ€™s adjective cellar? Here are six to consider:
Application Essay Tips | Tip #1: Use fewer adjectives.</p>

<p>You have a word limit, so you have to be concise. Especially if your essayâ€™s running long, consider stripping out your adjectives. Focus on using the verbs to convey your meaning (just as John Kennedy Toole does in the opening lines of A Confederacy of Dunces). If you want to learn more about how to use verbs, note each verb Finney uses, and ponder the effect each verb creates.
Application Essay Tips | Tip #2: Pair â€œodd coupleâ€ words to make a comparison.</p>

<p>I donâ€™t usually associate â€œchihuahuaâ€ with â€œferocity.â€ Thatâ€™s why I consider these two words an odd couple. But to describe someone as mild-mannered, I might pair these odd couple words as follows: â€œHe has the ferocity of a chihuahua.â€ By pairing odd couple words to introduce an image, I make my comparison more vivid than saying, â€œHe is mild-mannered.â€ Finney is pairing odd couple words in a comparison when he writes that the adjective cellar had â€œthe grace of line of a fire hydrant.â€ This approach is better than just saying the adjective cellar was ugly.
Application Essay Tips | Tip #3: â€œLikeâ€ it!</p>

<p>I got tired of telling you to use a simile. Use the word like, and follow it with an image. Finney employs this technique at least five times in a very short article:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>â€œâ€¦like a magnetâ€¦â€</p>
