<p>Using â€œlikeâ€ is not quantum physics, though it is formulaic: Like + image = something an admission officer might actually enjoy reading.
Application Essay Tips | Tip #4: Consider irony.</p>

<p>Finneyâ€™s use of irony â€“ in this case, sarcasm â€“ adds humor. Iâ€™m not saying you should be sarcastic in a way that shows youâ€™re cynical or angst-ridden (to understand the importance of optimism, seeÂ my thoughts on Oscar Hammersteinâ€™s article). But if you can be ironic in a self-deprecating way, or in a way that shows your unique perspective, thatâ€™s great.
How does Finney use irony? In describing the effects of releasing a cloud of adjectives over the Senate, he remarks, â€œSomething must have gone wrong this time, though, for things didnâ€™t sound one bit different.â€ His comment is ironic because nothing has gone wrong; senators sound so pompous already that even a release of adjectives cannot make them sound more so. Also, Finney concludes by implying that the piece is a telegram and that he used the adjective cellar to compose it, â€œWhich is why itâ€™s so short, of course.â€ This closing sentence is ironic because, of course, Finneyâ€™s piece is ridiculously long for a telegram.
Perhaps youâ€™ll find a way to use irony in your essay either to poke fun at yourself or provide insight into one of your beliefs or activities. This approach is not for everyone, so if it doesnâ€™t suit you, move on.
Application Essay Tips | Tip #5: Ask â€œWhat if?â€</p>

<p>Finneyâ€™s whole piece is a whimsical response to the question, â€œWhat would happen if I had a magical device that collected adjectives?â€ He even goes so far as to imagine the adjectivesâ€™ colors: â€œYou canâ€™t see them at all unless the light is just right, and most of them are colorless. Some of them are delicate pastels, though. â€œVeryâ€, for example, is a pale pink; â€œlushâ€ is green, of course; and â€œindubitableâ€ is a dirty gray.â€ This absurd description is absurdly funny.
Of course, your college application essay is not a creative writing exercise, so Iâ€™m not suggesting you submit a creative writing sample. But as I explain in myÂ application essay ebook, the first step to writing the application essay is to figure out who you are. Finney is someone who hates the over-use of adjectives. He could have written, â€œIâ€™m someone who hates the over-use of adjectives.â€ That statement would be true, but it would bore us instantly. So he conveys his point of view by answering a whimsical â€œWhat if?â€ question.
