Application Essay Tips | Tip #6: Watch your tone.</p>

<p>Finneyâ€™s piece is pure nonsense. Thereâ€™s no such thing as an adjective cellar. Yet he describes it in an objective, clinical tone, as if itâ€™s a real phenomenon, even commenting on the colors of various adjectives and relaying the effects of adjectives that jump into Mrs. Gormanâ€™s conversation. Using a serious tone to describe a nonsensical topic makes the piece funny.
Figuring out tone is challenging because tone results from the cumulative effect of all the sentences you write. But Iâ€™m not mentioning tone to stress you out. The opposite, actually. The whole purpose of your application essay is to reveal your personality. You should use whatever tone accomplishes that goal. Maybe it will be a serious tone. Maybe funny. Or maybe mostly serious. Whatever it ends up being, never assume that a serious tone is the â€œrightâ€ tone for an application essay. The right tone is the one that reveals â€“ not conceals â€“ your unique personality. If writing in a 100% serious makes you sound like someone else, you have to reconsider your approach.
