Letâ€™s say we agree that heÂ isÂ straight. In that case, he willÂ stillÂ most-often have sex with women, but heâ€™ll remember this one time, at the age of 17, when he had sex with a man.
That will happen if we say heÂ isÂ bisexual, asexual, pansexual, or a klingon. Weâ€™ll change nothing about his traits or actions by labeling him. Nor will we say anything useful or interesting about him.
Perhaps when he asks, â€œAm I gay?â€ he means something coherent like, â€œGiven the facts of my life, will most peopleÂ labelÂ me as gay?â€ We canâ€™t tell what he means, because he expressed himself with a form of â€œto be.â€
When we write or speak â€œto be,â€ we often muddle our conversations, prose, and our thinking.
Examples:</p>
<ul>
  <li>If we find organisms on Mars that appear to be alive, how will we know they reallyÂ arealive?</li>
  <li>Is it true that the Beatles reallyÂ areÂ objectively the best band ever?</li>
  <li>WhatÂ isÂ good writing?
We could clarified (or reveal the meaninglessness of) all these questions by rewriting them so that instead of saying what XÂ is,Â they focused on what XÂ doesÂ or the traits XÂ has.
I spent a year forcing myself to write in E-prime, and it helped me think and write much more clearly. During that year, I followed these additional rules: (a) I forbade myself from telling anyone about E-prime or my decision to write in it, and (b) I pledged to make my prose read so naturally, no one would noticed anything odd about it.
