<p>Here are some problems: - Itâ€™s full of what I call â€œinert phrases.â€ Examples are â€œadditionally, it is more necessary for,â€ â€œThis is because the,â€ â€œsince there are always some,â€ and â€œis another factor that makes the abilityâ€¦â€œÂ  Non-inert phases tell who is doing what to whom: â€œBob ate the apple,â€ â€œI own seven dogs and two cats,â€ â€œJenny stole Mikeâ€™s wallet.â€ They are easy to grasp.Â  When a row of words contains no imageryâ€“no agent doing something and/or no object being acted on or describedâ€“the reader starts to tune out. Weâ€™re sensual creatures, best able to imagine the things we can touch, taste, smell, hear, and see.Â  In my own writing, I canâ€™t eliminate all inert phrases. But as I redraft, I look for them and cut any that I can, often rewriting sentences so that theyâ€™re centered around an active agent.Â  Thatâ€™s the key. For each sentence, ask who or what isÂ doingÂ something. Usually, thereâ€™s an agent, and you can redraft the sentence to bring him, her, they, or it to the forefront.Â  - Youâ€™re spending too much time revving up. You donâ€™t need to start each sentence with words like â€œadditionallyâ€ and phrases like â€œthis is because.â€ I understand that youâ€™re trying to link ideas togetherâ€“to show how one leads to the other. But just get to the point. The reader will supply the link himself. (This is a general rule. Sometimes you have to help the reader understand that A causes B or that B is an exception to Aâ€™s rule. Most of the time, itâ€™s clear.) Compareâ€¦ There was no coffee left. Bob grabbed his car keys and drove to the store. â€¦ with â€¦ There was no coffee left. Due to this lack and the fact that he wanted coffee, Bob grabbed his car keys and drove to the store. Hereâ€™s my rewrite:</p>

