<p>Revisiting â€œshow donâ€™t tell.â€
On reddit, a writer explained that â€œshow donâ€™t tellâ€ applies to character action and emotion, but not description. He makes some good points, and itâ€™s worth reading.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.reddit.com/r/writing/comments/1yg7oa/a_clarification_of_the_everpopular_show_dont_tell/">Reddit discussion</a></p>

<p>Hereâ€™s my response:</p>

<p>This is a good rule of thumb, because if people follow it, their fiction will likely improve. However, I disagree that â€œshow donâ€™t tellâ€ is only useful for character writing.</p>

<p>At least when I write, my goal is to give the reader a sensual (or sensory) and visceral experience. I want him to feel like heâ€™s there (whether â€œthereâ€ is a saloon, the deck of a space ship, a Manhattan apartment, or inside the head of a character). That is, I want put him in the environment rather than give him a report about whatâ€™s going on in the environment.</p>

<p>Thatâ€™s the difference:</p>

<p>Goal of telling: explaining to the reader the latest facts about WWI.
Goal of showing: forcing him to crouch in the trenches, mud up to his knees, covering his ears as grenades explode around him.</p>

<p>â€œShowing,â€ in my formulation, is anything that puts the reader there. Itâ€™s anything that licks his face, tickles his ribs, wafts the stench of urine in his nostrils, or fucks him up the ass.</p>

<p>You can succeed or fail at showing in a variety of ways. For instance, you can fail by not providing enough detail, by providing too much (so that the reader is overwhelmed), or by providing the wrong kind, e.g. cliches like â€œfluffy cloud,â€ which the reader passes over without experiencing anything.</p>

<p>Your post is helpful, because characterization is where many writers fail. (â€œShe was angry,â€ etc.), but itâ€™s not the only point of failure.</p>

<p>Telling: It was hailing.</p>

<p>Showing: Hail pelted the windows.</p>

<p>The first version just gives information. The second puts you there.</p>

<p>One neednâ€™t always show and not tell. In fact, thatâ€™s a bad idea, because if every detail is shown, then no detail will stand out as more important than others. Perhaps, in a given story, itâ€™s not important for the reader to feel raindrops: â€œIt was raining, so she knew this would be yet another spent on the sofa, flipping channels, only budging to get beer from the fridge and to peeâ€¦â€</p>

<p>Or the rain might be the main point: â€œWater exploded out of the sky, drenching her yard and pounding on her roof, and so she stayed inside on the sofa.â€ As writers, we control whatâ€™s in focus and whatâ€™s blurred in the background.</p>

<p>The key is to remember that humans are sensual creatures, and if we go too long without hearing, seeing, smelling, tasting, touching or moving (the kinetic sense), we tend to tune out. So while every sentence neednâ€™t (and shouldnâ€™t) be a sensual experience (except, perhaps, in the case of some short poetry), itâ€™s worth always asking, â€œHow long has it been since I grabbed the reader by the balls?â€</p>

<p>Often, telling works best as a thesis statement or a punch line. Thesis statement: â€œIt was raining, soâ€¦ [insert showing].â€ Punchline: â€œ[insert showingâ€] â€¦ which is why she stayed home.â€</p>

<p>Specific rules, like â€œdonâ€™t use too many adverbs,â€ may help beginning writers, but ultimately there are no rules: just goals. If, as with me, your goal is to put the reader there, you must go through your draft, sentence by sentence, phrase by phrase, word by word, and ask if youâ€™re achieving your goals. Is this adverb putting the reader there? Is this sensual detail failing to do so, because itâ€™s a cliche. Could this image be sharper? Or am a purposefully â€œtelling,â€ as a setup the for sensory detail thatâ€™s to follow? Or am I delivering a punchline (a â€œsumming up,â€ a conclusionâ€¦) after making the reader have a series of sensations.</p>

<p>Above, I used the phrase â€œsensory detail,â€ but even thatâ€™s wrong. That makes it sound like the goal is to list the color of everything or to give all sorts of micro descriptions. Thatâ€™s not the goal. The goal is to use every technique in your arsenal to make the reader have experiences. Sensory/sensual details are one tool. Word sounds are another: Boom! Hiss! Crackle! Sentence structure is another. Pacing is another. Subtext (craftily omitted details) is yet another.</p>

<p>Rather than â€œshow donâ€™t tell,â€ perhaps we should say, â€œPunch the reader in the face; donâ€™t explain to him that a fight occurred.â€</p>

